# <%= current_page.data.title %>

The purpose of this document is to define our standards for writing terraform in Analytical Platform repositories.

As a contributor to the Analytical Platform you will find places where these standards don't apply. This is a consequence of many contributors committing to our code over many years. The below sets out our standards going forward and helps introduce them to any new joiners to the team.

## Naming

Naming things is famously hard! We have a few basic rules we adhere to when naming things.

### File names

Named files for resources should be plural, for example: 'iam-roles.tf' or 'iam-policies.tf'.

Example:

✅ `s3-buckets.tf`

❌ `s3.tf` OR `buckets.tf` OR `bucket.tf`

We do not use `main.tf`.

### Resource and module names

Module or resource names should be written in snake_case.

Example:

✅ `module "example_s3"`

❌ `module "example-s3"`

❌ `module "ExampleS3"`

## Repository structure

Create similar resources in the same `.tf` file. This means all S3 buckets in a component should be created in `s3-buckets.tf` for example.

If a resource is brand new, create a new file and adopt a sensible name as per this document.

### Required Terraform files

These files form the foundation for terraform to run (in each of its respective locations)

`variables.tf`

```terraform
variable "account_ids" {
  type        = map(string)
  description = "Map of account names to account IDs"
}

variable "tags" {
  type        = map(string)
  description = "Map of tags to apply to resources"
}
```

`data.tf`

```terraform
data "aws_caller_identity" "session" {
  provider = aws.session
}

data "aws_iam_session_context" "session" {
  provider = aws.session

  arn = data.aws_caller_identity.session.arn
}
```

`terraform.tfvars`

```terraform
account_ids = {
  ${AWS_ACCOUNT_NAME}                       = "${AWS_ACCOUNT_ID}"
  analytical-platform-management-production = "042130406152"
}

tags = {
  business-unit          = "Platforms"
  application            = "Data Platform"
  component              = "${COMPONENT}"
  environment            = "${ENVIRONMENT}"
  is-production          = "${IS_PRODUCTION}"
  owner                  = "data-platform:data-platform-tech@digital.justice.gov.uk"
  infrastructure-support = "data-platform:data-platform-tech@digital.justice.gov.uk"
  source-code            = "github.com/ministryofjustice/analytical-platform/terraform/aws/${AWS_ACCOUNT_NAME}/${COMPONENT}"
}
```

`terraform.tf`

```terraform
terraform {
  backend "s3" {
    acl            = "private"
    bucket         = "global-tf-state-aqsvzyd5u9"
    encrypt        = true
    key            = "aws/${AWS_ACCOUNT_NAME}/${COMPONENT}/terraform.tfstate"
    region         = "eu-west-2"
    dynamodb_table = "global-tf-state-aqsvzyd5u9-locks"
  }

  required_providers {
    aws = {
      source  = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = "${LATEST_VERSION}" # e.g. 5.9.0 can be found at https://registry.terraform.io/providers/hashicorp/aws/latest
    }
  }

  required_version = "~> 1.5"
}

provider "aws" {
  alias = "session"
}

provider "aws" {
  region = "eu-west-2"

  assume_role {
    role_arn = "arn:aws:iam::${var.account_ids["${AWS_ACCOUNT_NAME}"]}:role/GlobalGitHubActionAdmin"
  }

  default_tags {
    tags = var.tags
  }
}

provider "aws" {
  alias  = "analytical-platform-management-production"
  region = "eu-west-2"

  assume_role {
    role_arn = can(regex("AdministratorAccess", data.aws_iam_session_context.session.issuer_arn)) ? null : "arn:aws:iam::${var.account_ids["analytical-platform-management-production"]}:role/GlobalGitHubActionAdmin"
  }

  default_tags {
    tags = var.tags
  }
}
```

`locals.tf`

```terraform
locals {
  name = "example"
}
```

The above does not apply in Modernisation Platform Environments repository, we abide by the standards of that repository for foundational files.

## Tagging

The `default_tags` in `terraform.tf` ensures that every AWS resource created with this provider automatically gets the tags you’ve defined in `terraform.tfvars`.

## Defining policies

Our pattern for defining policies is as follows:

```terraform
data "aws_iam_policy_document" "example" {
  ...
}

module "example_iam_policy" {
  source  = "terraform-aws-modules/iam/aws//modules/iam-policy"
  version = "6.1.2"

  name_prefix = "name-of-policy"

  policy = data.aws_iam_policy_document.example.json
}
```

### Managing multiple policy documents

Repeat the pattern when there are multiple policy documents in a single file. For example, you would define them as follows:

```terraform
data "aws_iam_policy_document" "another_example" {
  ...
}

module "example_iam_policy" {
  source  = "terraform-aws-modules/iam/aws//modules/iam-policy"
  version = "6.1.2"

  name_prefix = "name-of-another-policy"

  policy = data.aws_iam_policy_document.another_example.json
}
```

See an [example of multiple policies in a single file](https://github.com/ministryofjustice/analytical-platform/blob/main/terraform/aws/analytical-platform-data-production/ingestion-egress/iam-policies.tf).


